ciguatera fish poisoning results from the bioconcentration of a variety of toxins produced by marine dinoflagellatessigns and symptoms vary widely but it usually presents as gastrointestinal and neurologic complaints beginning shortly after the ingestion of fish containing the toxinssymptoms may persist for months and sometimes even yearsalthough cases have been reported throughout the united states epidemics are most common along tropical and subtropical coasts and usually involve the ingestion of large carnivorous fishwe review the literature and report the first epidemic of 25 cases of ciguatera fish poisoning presenting to area hospitals in southern california that were successfully tracked by the department of health services and isolated to fish caught off the coast of baja california mexico